## Chesterton check (why dropping the SQLite invalidate call is safe)
- `git log -S invalidate_ttl_cache -- sqlite_trace_server.py` -> added in
  14bc4a1a54 (#6181 "add TTL settings GET/POST API endpoints"), no git note.
- get_project_retention_days (the ONLY populator of _project_ttl_cache) is called
  only by clickhouse_trace_server_batched + TTL unit tests; SQLite uses its own
  uncached _get_project_retention_days. So SQLite never populates/reads that cache;
  invalidating it is a no-op in a SQLite deployment. Added for CH parity.
- Cache test-isolation is handled by reset_ttl_cache() fixtures, not by this call.

